caption:
Subaru has a long-term partnership with Toyota, and their Solterra is a sibling vehicle to our bZ4X. 
Check out these two BEVs visiting iconic Toyota locations in Japan.

Toyota Automobile Museum
A museum dedicated to introducing visitors to automotive culture and history from around the world.

Toyoda Kiichiro’s Former Residence
The private residence of Toyota’s founder.

Toyota Ohashi Bridge
A bridge connecting Toyoda-shi Station to Toyoda Stadium, located near Toyota Headquarters.

Toyota Commemorative Museum of Industry and Technology
A museum featuring exhibits showcasing the evolution of automotive manufacturing technology.

Nagoya Castle
Constructed in 1615. The first castle in Japan to be designated a National Treasure.

Toyota Motomachi Plant
Passenger vehicle automotive plant that began operation in 1959. Manufactures both the bZ4X and the Solterra.

The former residence of Subaru founder Chikuhei Nakajima.

SUBARU Visitor Center
A facility featuring exhibits focused on Subaru’s history, technology, and safety initiatives.

Art Museum & Library, Ota
An iconic art museum and library located close to the Subaru main factory.

Iseya
A shop that makes and sells traditional sweets decorated with Subaru motifs.

The lack of a more powerful engine option, such as the 2.8-liter engine, poses serious safety concerns, especially when attempting to overtake larger vehicles or when towing a trailer.
